{{infobox ethnic group |group = African immigration to Norway<!-- [[WP:NOETHNICGALLERIES]] --> |population = 97,152<ref name="Statnorpim">[http://www.ssb.no/en/innvbef/ Statistics Norway - Immigrants and Norwegian-born to immigrant parents, 1 January 2014]</ref> |region1 = [[Oslo]] |langs = [[Norwegian language|Norwegian]], [[Afroasiatic languages]], [[Niger–Congo languages]], [[Nilo-Saharan languages]] |rels = [[Christianity]], [[Islam]] }} '''African immigration to Norway''' refers to [[Immigration|immigrants]] to [[Norway]] from [[Africa]]. An estimated 88,764 people in Norway are either first or second generation immigrants from Africa.<ref name="Statnorpim"/>
==Distribution== ===North and Northeast Africans=== Immigration from countries in Africa to Norway grew slightly from the end of the 1980s, but grew markedly from 2000 onwards. The growth is owed mainly to a rise in the number of immigrants from North and Northeast Africa, including [[Somalis in Norway|Somalia]] (25,496), [[Moroccans in Norway|Morocco]] (8,058), [[Eritreans in Norway|Eritrea]] (5,789) and [[Ethiopians in Norway|Ethiopia]] (5,156).<ref name="Statnor2010"/>
===Other Africans=== Compared to North and Northeast Africans, the percentage of Africans from other regions as a proportion of recent immigrants to Norway from Africa is relatively low.
Most other Africans in Norway come from [[West Africa]], especially [[Ghana]] (2,034), [[Gambia]] (1,409) and [[Nigeria]] (1,247).<ref name="Statnor2010"/> There is also a sizeable population of Africans from the [[Democratic Republic of the Congo]] (2,050).
