{{Infobox language |name=Bankan Tey |nativename=Walo-Kumbe |region=[[Mali]] |speakers={{sigfig|1320|2}} |date=1998 census |ref=e18 |familycolor=Niger-Congo |fam2=[[Dogon languages|Dogon]] |fam3=Nanga |iso3=dbw |glotto=bank1259 |glottorefname=Bankan Tey Dogon }}
'''Bankan Tey Dogon''', at first called '''Walo-Kumbe Dogon''' after the two main villages it is spoken in, also known as '''Walo''' and '''Walonkore''', is a divergent, recently described [[Dogon language]] spoken in [[Mali]]. It was first reported online by Roger Blench,[https://web.archive.org/web/20130615111624/http://www.rogerblench.info/Language/Niger-Congo/Dogon/Dogon%20page.htm] who reports that it is "clearly related to [[Nanga Dogon|Nanga]]", which is only known from one report from 1953.
A third village investigated at the time, Been, speaks a related but lexically distinct form, [[Ben Tey Dogon]].
==References== {{Reflist}} * {{cite journal |last1=Blench |first1=Roger |authorlink=Roger Blench |title=A survey of Dogon languages in Mali: Overview |journal=OGMIOS: Newsletter of Foundation for Endangered Languages |year=2005 |volume=3.02 |issue=26 |pages=14–15 |publisher= |doi= |url=http://www.ogmios.org/ogmios_files/266.htm |accessdate=2011-06-30 }}. * {{cite book |last1=Hochstetler |first1=J. Lee |last2=Durieux |first2=J.A. |author3=E.I.K. Durieux-Boon |year=2004 |title=Sociolinguistic Survey of the Dogon Language Area |publisher=SIL International |url=http://www.sil.org/silesr/2004/silesr2004-004.pdf |accessdate=2011-06-30 }}
